B.LT=new A.cr("The Rule","Normal MUAPs have 2-4 phases. >4 phases is considered polyphasic.")
B.LB=new A.cr("The Standard","Up to 10% of MUAPs can be polyphasic in completely healthy muscle. Don't overcall it.")
B.LX=new A.cr("The Sound","A higher-frequency, somewhat 'clicky' or 'scratchy' sound due to the rapid baseline crossings.")
B.LL=new A.cr("The Significance","It is simply a measure of desynchronization. It does NOT distinguish between neuropathy and myopathy.")
B.a17=s([B.LT,B.LB,B.LX,B.LL],t.LK)
B.aal=new A.k_("Polyphasic Potentials","A normal motor unit fires its fibers synchronously. When they lose that synchrony\u2014either because the nerve is trying to reinnervate new fibers (neuropathy) or fibers are sick and dropping out (myopathy)\u2014you get a complex, jagged waveform.","liNujyDKe58",B.a17)
B.LY=new A.cr("The Normal Ratio","Generally ~5:1 (firing rate to the number of active MUAPs).")
B.LS=new A.cr("Reduced Recruitment","The hallmark of axonal loss (neuropathy). The patient only has a few motor units left, so to generate force, they must fire those remaining units incredibly fast (e.g., 1 unit firing at 20Hz).")
B.LQ=new A.cr("Early Recruitment","The hallmark of myopathy. Each motor unit is weak (fibers died), so the CNS has to recruit many units instantly just to generate minimal force.")
B.LN=new A.cr("Poor Activation","A central issue (pain, Upper Motor Neuron lesion). The patient fires one unit at a slow rate (e.g., 5Hz) and refuses to activate more units or fire faster.")
B.a_V=s([B.LY,B.LS,B.LQ,B.LN],t.LK)
B.aae=new A.k_("Motor Unit Recruitment","Recruitment is the single most important tool you have to differentiate a nerve problem from a muscle problem. Does the patient fire one extremely fast unit, or do they immediately recruit fifty tiny units?","kTJiD1d0NsI",B.a_V)
B.a2Z=s([B.aal,B.aae],t.ND)
