a0=A.cf("Anterior Interosseous Nerve Syndrome",a2,s2,"CRITICAL (NCS is normal in pure AIN)",A.a([A.t(!1,"Spared (Not AIN-innervated)",f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h5,h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.t(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,h8,h9,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,w7,"AIN",f0,"Absent/Severely Reduced",i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,f0,"Flexor Digitorum Profundus 2","AIN",f0,h4,i0,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,w3,"AIN",f0,h4,i0,f0),A.t(!1,"Spared (Proximal to AIN)",f0,f0,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,f0,o8,f0)],n),"AIN syndrome is a pure motor neuropathy. The hallmark is the inability to flex the distal phalanges of the thumb (FPL) and index finger (FDP 2), resulting in a characteristic 'pincer' pinch instead of a round 'OK' sign. Because the AIN carries no cutaneous sensory fibers, the NCS is characteristically normal, making EMG of the AIN-innervated muscles (FPL, FDP 2, PQ) the definitive diagnostic tool.",a1,"ain",a3,ae8,ae7,!0,a0,A.a(["AIN syndrome (Kiloh-Nevin) involves only the motor branch of the median nerve supplying the FPL, FDP 2/3, and PQ.","Crucial Clinical Pearl: AIN syndrome has NO sensory loss. If the patient has numbness, look for PTS or CTS.","NCS studies (Median sensory and motor to APB) are characteristically NORMAL in AIN syndrome.","The diagnosis is made solely on EMG, showing denervation only in the AIN-innervated triad (FPL, FDP 2, PQ)."],af3),"Difficulty Making the 'OK' Sign")
ae7=A.ce(55,"Pain in the mid-arm and weakness in the hand and wrist",i1,"Developed deep, aching pain in the medial mid-arm about 4 inches above the elbow. Over several weeks, noticed numbness in the thumb, index, and middle fingers and difficulty gripping objects. No neck pain.",i4,"House Painter",i4)
ae8=A.ci("Mild atrophy of the thenar eminence and the proximal volar forearm muscles.","A hard, bony prominence is palpable on the medial humerus approximately 5cm proximal to the medial epicondyle. Tenderness on pressure over this site reproduces 'shocks' to the thumb.",v4,v3,"Decreased sensation in the median distribution (digits 1-3.5) AND the central palm (palmar cutaneous territory).","Positive Tinel's sign at the mid-humerus site.","Right Pronator Teres 3/5, Flexor Carpi Radialis (FCR) 3/5, Flexor Pollicis Longus (FPL) 3/5, APB 3/5. Sparing of triceps and biceps.")
a3=A.a([A.V(w8,d9),A.V(v5,"PTS occurs at the elbow and WOULD SPARE the Pronator Teres muscle (first median branch); here the PT is weak, localizing the lesion more proximally to the humerus."),A.V(v6,"CTS involves the wrist and spares the forearm muscles (FCR, FPL, PT) and the palm; here all are involved."),A.V("C6-C7 Radiculopathy","Radiculopathy would commonly involve the Brachioradialis (C6) and show neck pain; here the BR is normal and there is a bony humeral spur palpable."),A.V("Arcade of Struthers (Ulnar)","A potential terminological confusion; Arcade of Struthers affects the Ulnar nerve, causing pinky numbness; this case involves the median distribution.")],ae9)
a1=A.a6(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Medial arm pain.","neurological","Hand weakness and numbness involving the thumb/index fingers."],af1,af1)
a2=A.a(["None."],af3)
a2=A.cg(A.a(["X-ray Right Humerus: Presence of a Supracondylar Process (bony spur) on the anteromedial surface of the humerus proximal to the epicondyle.","MRI Arm: Hyperintensity and swelling of the median nerve at the site of the supracondylar process."],af3),a2)
