c1=A.cf("Right S1 Radiculopathy",c3,k0,e2,A.a([A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,h3,m4,m5,f0,h4,m6,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,h3,ad2,ad3,f0,h4,r4,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,q4,f0,p1,ad4,f0,f0,p1,"S1",f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,l5,l6,f0,f0,l7,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,m0,l6,f0,f0,m1,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,m2,q6,f0,f0,m1,f0),A.t(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,m7,m8,f0,f0,q8,f0)],n),"Right S1 radiculopathy characterized by lower back pain radiating to the lateral foot, an absent right Achilles reflex, and weak plantarflexion. The diagnosis is confirmed by 1) Preserved SNAPs (Sural), 2) H-reflex delay, and 3) Denervation in the S1 myotome muscles (Gastroc, Gluteus Maximus) and S1 paraspinals.",c2,"s1radiculopathy",c4,ae8,ae7,!0,c1,A.a(["S1 radiculopathy classically presents with a diminished or absent Achilles reflex (S1 arc).","The H-reflex is the electrophysiological equivalent of the Achilles reflex and is a sensitive marker for S1 root dysfunction.","Normal Sural SNAP in the setting of S1 sensory loss localizes the lesion as pre-ganglionic (at the root level)."],af3),"Lower Back Pain with Foot Weakness")
ae7=A.ce(48,"8-month history of progressive numbness and weakness in right hand with neck pain",i1,"Symptoms include numbness in ring and little fingers, weakness gripping objects, and neck pain radiating down right arm. Recently developed difficulty with fine motor tasks like typing. Symptoms worse with prolonged computer use and overhead activities.","Metformin, gabapentin","Software Programmer","Cervical disc disease, Type 2 Diabetes")
ae8=A.ci("Mild atrophy of right hand intrinsics (FDI and Hypothenar).","Tenderness over the cubital tunnel and cervical paraspinals.","Triceps reflex 1+ on right, 2+ on left. Other reflexes symmetric.","Cervical extension reproduces right arm radiation.","Decreased sensation in C8 and Ulnar distributions (medial hand/forearm).","Positive Tinel's at elbow. Positive Spurling's test (right).","Right FDI 3/5, ADM 4/5. Extensor Indicis Proprius (EIP) 4/5. Flexor Carpi Ulnaris (FCU) 4/5.")
c4=A.a([A.V("Double Crush Syndrome",d9),A.V("C8 Radiculopathy (Isolated)","An isolated C8 radiculopathy would not explain the focal conduction block and significant 43% amplitude drop across the elbow."),A.V("Cubital Tunnel Syndrome (Isolated)","A cubital tunnel lesion cannot explain the weakness and denervation in the EIP (Radial nerve, C8) or the C8 paraspinal muscles."),A.V("Lower Trunk Brachial Plexopathy","Lower trunk plexopathy would involve multiple cord/nerve contributions and typically shows an abnormal Medial Antebrachial Cutaneous (MAC) SNAP; here the MAC is normal, localizing the second lesion to the root."),A.V(ad8,"TOS usually causes lower trunk symptoms and is often associated with vascular symptoms or a cervical rib; the normal MAC here rules out the lower trunk.")],ae9)
