c7=A.cf("Piriformis Syndrome / Sciatic Neuropathy at the Notch",c9,s2,ae1,A.a([A.t(!0,f0,f0,j8,f0,f0,m4,m5,f0,h4,m6,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,l5,l6,f0,h4,q3,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,m0,l6,f0,h4,q5,f0),A.t(!0,f0,f0,h2,f0,f0,m2,q6,f0,h4,m1,f0),A.t(!1,"Spared (rules out S1 root/plexus)",f0,f0,f0,f0,ad2,ad3,f0,f0,r4,f0),A.t(!1,"Spared (rules out L5 root/plexus)",f0,f0,f0,f0,q9,r0,f0,f0,l7,f0),A.t(!1,aa6,f0,f0,f0,f0,m7,m8,f0,f0,m9,f0),A.t(!1,"Spared (rules out radiculopathy)",f0,f0,f0,f0,ae4,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0)],n),"Compression of the sciatic nerve as it passes through or under the piriformis muscle. Diagnosis is confirmed by weakness in the sciatic distribution (leg/foot) with sparing of the proximal gluteal muscles and normal lumbar paraspinals. The H-reflex may be delayed, especially in positions of piriformis tension (FAIR test).",c8,"piriformis",d0,ae8,ae7,!0,c7,A.a(["Piriformis syndrome involves compression of the sciatic nerve at the sciatic notch, often exacerbated by hip internal rotation/adduction.","Localization Pearl: Sparing of the Gluteus Maximus (Inferior Gluteal nerve) and Normal Paraspinals distinguishes this from an S1 radiculopathy.","H-reflex testing in the FAIR position (Flexion, Adduction, Internal Rotation) can increase diagnostic sensitivity by physically compressing the nerve during the test.","Normal Sural SNAP would be expected in radiculopathy; in piriformis syndrome (post-ganglionic), it is often abnormal."],af3),"Deep Buttock Pain and Hip Weakness")
ae7=A.ce(48,"Chronic, deep heel pain that doesn't improve with stretching.",i1,"Persistent pain on the medial aspect of the heel for 8 months. Initially diagnosed as plantar fasciitis, but treatments (orthotics, injections) have failed. Pain is sharp and shooting, especially during a run. No back pain. No numbness in the toes.",x1,"Long-distance Runner","Recurrent Plantar Fasciitis")
ae8=A.ci("Normal arch height. No obvious atrophy of the intrinsic foot muscles.","Maximal tenderness over the medial calcaneal tuberosity and along the course of the first branch of the lateral plantar nerve. No tenderness at the Achilles insertion.",ad9,"Full ROM of the ankle and foot.","Normal sensation throughout the foot, including the medial and lateral plantar distributions (this nerve is primarily motor/pain).","Negative Windlass test. Tinel's sign present over the proximal course of the inferior calcaneal nerve.","5/5 strength in TA, EHL, and Gastrocnemius. Weakness in abduction of the 5th toe (ADQ) compared to the left. 5/5 hip and knee strength.")
d0=A.a([A.V("Baxter's Neuropathy (Inferior Calcaneal Nerve)",d9),A.V(ac8,"While commonly co-existing, isolated plantar fasciitis would NOT cause weakness or neurogenic EMG findings in the ADQ muscle."),A.V(ac9,"TTS would involve the entire medial or lateral plantar nerves, causing sensory loss on the sole of the foot and weakness in multiple intrinsic muscles (AH, FDB)."),A.V(ad0,"Radiculopathy would involve the Gastrocnemius and potentially cause a decreased Achilles reflex. This patient has normal strength and reflexes.")],ae9)
c8=A.a6(["constitutional","Negative.","musculoskeletal","Chronic heel pain.","neurological","Deep stabbing pain. No toe numbness."],af1,af1)
c9=A.a(["None."],af3)
c9=A.cg(A.a(["MRI Foot: Edema and atrophy of the Abductor Digiti Quinti (ADQ) muscle; associated with mild plantar fasciitis."],af3),c9)
d1=A.a([A.ac(!1,y7,h7,k5,g6,i7),A.ac(!1,q0,h7,k7,p4,aa4),A.ac(!1,"10","Often normal as the entrapment is motor-heavy",ad1,p3,j0)],q)
